\begin{abstract}
When a multi-stage NLP pipeline---tokenizer, POS tagger, dependency parser, NER, downstream classifier---exhibits a behavioral inconsistency under a meaning-preserving input transformation, every existing testing tool can detect the inconsistency but none can identify which stage caused it. We present \textsc{MetamorFault}, a grammar-compiled metamorphic testing engine whose central contribution is \emph{causal-differential fault localization} across multi-stage NLP inference pipelines. The engine generates linguistically-controlled test inputs via a probabilistic unification grammar, applies 15 meaning-preserving transformations (passivization, clefting, topicalization, etc.), instruments per-stage intermediate representations, and performs causal-differential analysis to identify which stage \emph{introduced} or \emph{amplified} each inconsistency. A grammar-aware shrinker produces minimal counterexamples that maintain grammaticality and transformation applicability. On fault-injected spaCy and HuggingFace pipelines, \textsc{MetamorFault} achieves 89.2\% fault localization accuracy (vs.\ 0\% for CheckList and TextFlint, which do not localize), produces counterexamples 73\% smaller than string-level shrinking, and finds bugs 3.2$\times$ faster than random testing through algebraic coverage optimization. The engine also generates a \emph{behavioral atlas}: a public database mapping (transformation $\times$ pipeline $\times$ NLP task) triples to behavioral outcomes. \textsc{MetamorFault} is implemented in 107K lines of Rust and Python.
\end{abstract}

% ============================================================================
\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:intro}
% ============================================================================

Production NLP systems are rarely monolithic models. A typical deployment chains multiple processing stages: a tokenizer segments raw text, a POS tagger assigns grammatical categories, a dependency parser constructs syntactic structure, a named entity recognizer identifies entities, and a downstream classifier or extractor produces the final output. When such a pipeline exhibits a behavioral inconsistency---passivizing a sentence flips an entity label, adding an adverb changes sentiment---the NLP engineer faces a debugging challenge fundamentally different from single-model testing: \emph{which stage caused the inconsistency?}

Existing metamorphic testing tools for NLP---CheckList~\cite{ribeiro2020checklist}, TextFlint~\cite{gui2021textflint}, Robustness Gym~\cite{goel2021robustness}, TextAttack~\cite{morris2020textattack}, NL-Augmenter~\cite{dhole2021nlaugmenter}---apply meaning-preserving transformations and report end-to-end pass/fail. They are thermometers: they detect that the pipeline is ``sick'' but cannot diagnose the disease. An engineer who discovers that passivizing a sentence flips an entity label knows \emph{that} the pipeline is broken, but not \emph{whether} the fault originates in the tokenizer, the tagger, the parser, or the NER model---and not whether the parser merely amplified a tagger error or introduced a new one.

This distinction---between \emph{introduction} and \emph{amplification} of faults across pipeline stages---is the central challenge. Spectrum-based fault localization (SBFL)~\cite{jones2002visualization,abreu2009spectrum} is well-studied for traditional software, but NLP pipelines violate its assumptions: ``coverage'' is not statement execution but linguistic feature processing, and pipeline stages interact through complex intermediate representations (parse trees, dependency graphs, embedding vectors) rather than shared memory.

\textsc{MetamorFault} bridges this gap. We contribute:

\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*]
\item \textbf{Causal-differential fault localization (M4):} A novel synthesis of SBFL with interventional causal reasoning that distinguishes fault introduction from fault amplification across NLP pipeline stages (\S\ref{sec:formal}).
\item \textbf{Grammar-constrained shrinking (M5):} A delta debugging algorithm operating on parse trees with grammaticality and transformation-applicability constraints, producing 1-minimal counterexamples with convergence bounds (\S\ref{sec:formal}).
\item \textbf{Transformation algebra:} A composable algebra of 15 meaning-preserving transformations with statistical composition theorem (M3) enabling systematic coverage without exhaustive testing (\S\ref{sec:formal}).
\item \textbf{Behavioral Fragility Index (M7):} A per-stage metric quantifying how severely each pipeline stage amplifies perturbations (\S\ref{sec:formal}).
\item \textbf{Comprehensive evaluation:} Localization accuracy of 89.2\% on fault-injected pipelines, 73\% counterexample size reduction, and 3.2$\times$ coverage efficiency gain over random testing (\S\ref{sec:eval}).
\end{enumerate}


% ============================================================================
\section{Background}
\label{sec:background}
% ============================================================================

\subsection{Metamorphic Testing for NLP}

Metamorphic testing~\cite{chen2018metamorphic} validates software by checking \emph{metamorphic relations} (MRs): if input $x$ is transformed to $\tau(x)$ in a meaning-preserving way, then the output should satisfy a known relationship. For NLP, typical MRs include: entity labels should be preserved under passivization (NER), polarity should be preserved under synonym substitution (sentiment analysis), and dependency structure should change predictably under clefting (parsing).

CheckList~\cite{ribeiro2020checklist} introduced a template-based approach to MR testing for NLP, with minimum functionality tests, invariance tests, and directional expectation tests. TextFlint~\cite{gui2021textflint} provides a unified platform for NLP robustness evaluation with task-specific transformation libraries. NL-Augmenter~\cite{dhole2021nlaugmenter} offers a community-contributed repository of 117+ transformations. All operate at the end-to-end level without pipeline-stage instrumentation.

\subsection{Fault Localization}

Spectrum-based fault localization (SBFL)~\cite{jones2002visualization} uses coverage information from passing and failing tests to rank program elements by suspiciousness. The Ochiai coefficient~\cite{abreu2009spectrum} is the most widely used suspiciousness metric:
\begin{equation}
\text{Ochiai}(e) = \frac{n_{ef}}{\sqrt{(n_{ef} + n_{nf}) \cdot (n_{ef} + n_{ep})}}
\end{equation}
where $n_{ef}$ is the number of failing tests covering element $e$, $n_{nf}$ is the number of failing tests not covering $e$, and $n_{ep}$ is the number of passing tests covering $e$.

\subsection{Delta Debugging}

Delta debugging~\cite{zeller2002simplifying} minimizes failure-inducing inputs by systematically removing subsets while preserving the failure. For structured inputs, hierarchical delta debugging (HDD)~\cite{misherghi2006hdd} operates on parse trees. TreeReduce~\cite{herfert2017treereduce} extends HDD for programming language ASTs but does not handle natural language's grammaticality constraints or linguistic feature unification.


