\subsection{Grammar Compiler}

The grammar compiler implements a probabilistic unification grammar for English that enforces agreement, subcategorization, and selectional restrictions. From a single grammar specification, the compiler produces two automata:

\begin{itemize}
\item A \emph{weighted recursive transition network} (RTN) for generation: forward sampling with Boltzmann distributions for naturalistic output.
\item A \emph{minimal-derivation lattice} for shrinking: backward search for smallest grammatical sub-derivations.
\end{itemize}

The unification engine implements Tomabechi/Wroblewski DAG unification with occurs-check over re-entrant feature structures. The morphological engine handles English inflection and irregular forms via finite-state transducers. Grammar naturalness is enforced through frequency-weighted lexical selection and a perplexity proxy (trigram model) constraining generation to sentences within 2$\times$ the perplexity of Penn Treebank text.

\subsection{Transformation Algebra}

Fifteen linguistically-grounded transformations form the initial release:

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{The 15 core transformations with preservation scope.}
\label{tab:transforms}
\small
\begin{tabular}{@{}rlp{4.5cm}@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{\#} & \textbf{Transformation} & \textbf{Preserves (for NER/Sentiment)} \\
\midrule
1 & Passivization & Entity ref, polarity \\
2 & Clefting & Entity ref, polarity \\
3 & Topicalization & Entity ref, polarity \\
4 & Relative clause insertion & Entity ref, polarity \\
5 & Relative clause deletion & Entity ref, polarity \\
6 & Tense change & Entity ref, polarity \\
7 & Agreement perturbation & Entity ref (violation-injecting) \\
8 & Synonym substitution & Entity ref, polarity \\
9 & Negation insertion & Entity ref \\
10 & Coordinated NP reorder & Entity ref, polarity \\
11 & PP attachment variation & Entity ref \\
12 & Adverb repositioning & Entity ref, polarity \\
13 & There-insertion & Entity ref, polarity \\
14 & Dative alternation & Entity ref, polarity \\
15 & Embedding depth change & Entity ref, polarity \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

Each transformation is implemented as a tree transduction rule (150--250 lines) operating on the unification grammar's parse trees. The algebra tracks composition properties: which pairs commute, which compositions preserve which semantic predicates.

\subsection{Pipeline Instrumentor}

Adapters for spaCy and HuggingFace Transformers (covering $\sim$80\% of production NLP pipelines) capture intermediate representations at each pipeline stage via copy-on-write snapshots with delta compression. A generic adapter supports arbitrary Python pipelines. The instrumentor records tokenization output, POS tags, dependency arcs, entity spans, and embedding vectors at each stage boundary.

\subsection{Causal-Differential Fault Localizer}

For each metamorphic violation, the localizer:
\begin{enumerate}
\item Computes per-stage differentials: the divergence between original and transformed intermediate representations at each stage boundary.
\item Applies spectrum-based fault localization (Ochiai coefficient) across the test corpus.
\item Performs causal refinement: replaces a suspected stage's output with the original execution's output and observes whether the downstream violation disappears.
\end{enumerate}

The causal refinement step is the key differentiator. It distinguishes: ``stage $k$ \emph{introduced} the fault'' (replacing stage $k$'s output eliminates the violation) from ``stage $k$ \emph{amplified} a fault from stage $k{-}1$'' (the violation persists with reduced magnitude even after replacement).

\subsection{Grammar-Aware Shrinker}

Parse-tree delta debugging maintains grammaticality at every step, preserves transformation applicability, and preserves the metamorphic violation. The shrinker operates on the minimal-derivation lattice from the grammar compiler, pruning sub-derivations that do not contribute to the violation. It produces 1-minimal counterexamples: no single subtree replacement further reduces the input.


% ============================================================================
\section{Formal Foundations}
\label{sec:formal}
% ============================================================================

\subsection{Transformation Algebra}

\begin{definition}[Transformation Algebra]
\label{def:algebra}
Let $\mathcal{S}$ be the set of grammatically valid sentences and $\mathcal{T} = \{\tau_1, \ldots, \tau_{15}\}$ the set of transformations. The transformation algebra $(\mathcal{T}^*, \circ, \text{id})$ is the free monoid over $\mathcal{T}$ quotiented by task-parameterized semantic equivalence: $\tau_i \circ \tau_j \sim \tau_j \circ \tau_i$ when $\tau_i, \tau_j$ modify disjoint syntactic positions.
\end{definition}

\begin{theorem}[MR Composition -- M3]
\label{thm:composition}
If transformations $\tau_1, \tau_2$ modify disjoint syntactic positions and satisfy task-parameterized meaning preservation independently, then their composition preserves meaning with probability $\geq 1 - \delta$, where $\delta$ is empirically bounded via Clopper-Pearson exact binomial confidence intervals. This reduces the required test count from $O(|\mathcal{T}|^2)$ to $O(|\mathcal{T}| \cdot \log|\mathcal{R}|)$ for pairwise coverage.
\end{theorem}

We deliberately weaken this from a deterministic guarantee to a statistical one: natural language meaning is notoriously non-compositional (idioms, collocations, scope interactions violate syntactic locality).

\subsection{Causal-Differential Fault Localization (M4)}

\begin{definition}[Per-Stage Differential]
\label{def:differential}
Given pipeline $P = s_1 \to s_2 \to \cdots \to s_n$, input $x$, and transformation $\tau$, the per-stage differential is:
\[
\Delta_k(x, \tau) = \text{dist}(s_k(\text{prefix}_k(x)),\; s_k(\text{prefix}_k(\tau(x))))
\]
where $\text{prefix}_k$ denotes the first $k{-}1$ stages, and dist is a task-specific distance function.
\end{definition}

\begin{theorem}[Causal-Differential Fault Localization]
\label{thm:localization}
Given pipeline $P = s_1 \to \cdots \to s_n$ and a metamorphic violation, the causal localizer identifies stage $k^*$:
\[
k^* = \arg\max_k \left[\Delta_k(x, \tau) - \mathbb{E}[\Delta_k \mid \tau \text{ is meaning-preserving}]\right]
\]
The causal refinement distinguishes introduction from amplification via interventional analysis: replace stage $k$'s output with the original execution's output $s_k(\text{prefix}_k(x))$ and observe the downstream behavior change $\delta_k$:
\[
\delta_k = \text{dist}(P(x),\; P_{[k \leftarrow \text{orig}]}(\tau(x)))
\]
If $\delta_k \approx 0$, stage $k$ introduced the fault. If $\delta_k > 0$ but $\delta_k < \text{dist}(P(x), P(\tau(x)))$, stage $k$ amplified a fault from an earlier stage.

Complexity: $O(N \cdot n \cdot C_{\text{pipeline}})$, linear in test count $N$ and stage count $n$.
\end{theorem}

\subsection{Grammar-Constrained Shrinking Convergence (M5)}

\begin{theorem}[GCHDD Convergence]
\label{thm:shrinking}
Grammar-Constrained Hierarchical Delta Debugging (GCHDD) terminates in $O(|T|^2 \cdot |R|)$ grammar-validity checks, each costing $O(|F|)$ for feature unification, where $|T|$ is the parse tree size, $|R|$ is the number of grammar rules, and $|F|$ is the feature structure size. GCHDD produces 1-minimal counterexamples: no single subtree replacement further reduces the input while maintaining grammaticality, transformation applicability, and the metamorphic violation.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}[Proof sketch]
At each iteration, GCHDD attempts to replace each subtree of the current parse tree $T$ with a smaller grammatically valid subtree from the minimal-derivation lattice. If no replacement reduces the tree, the algorithm terminates. Each iteration reduces $|T|$ by at least 1 node or terminates. The number of candidate replacements per iteration is $O(|T| \cdot |R|)$ (each subtree $\times$ each grammar rule producing a smaller derivation). Grammar-validity checking via unification costs $O(|F|)$ per candidate. Total: $O(|T|^2 \cdot |R| \cdot |F|)$ unification operations.
\end{proof}

\subsection{Behavioral Fragility Index (M7)}

\begin{definition}[Behavioral Fragility Index]
\label{def:bfi}
For pipeline $P$, transformation $\tau$, and stage $k$:
\[
\text{BFI}_k(P, \tau) = \frac{\mathbb{E}_x[\text{dist}_{\text{out},k}(s_k(x), s_k(\tau(x)))]}{\mathbb{E}_x[\text{dist}_{\text{in},k}(\text{prefix}_k(x), \text{prefix}_k(\tau(x)))]}
\]
BFI $\gg 1$ indicates stage $k$ amplifies the transformation's effect. BFI $\approx 1$ indicates stability. BFI $\ll 1$ indicates attenuation.
\end{definition}

The BFI is interpretable only relative to the task-specific MR that defines which behavioral dimensions should be invariant. A parser \emph{should} produce different trees for active vs.\ passive voice---high BFI on syntactic distance is \emph{expected} for passivization. High BFI on entity-label distance under passivization, however, indicates a fragility bug.


