\section{Implementation}
\label{sec:impl}
% ============================================================================

\textsc{MetamorFault} is implemented in approximately 107,000 lines of code:

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{Implementation breakdown by subsystem.}
\label{tab:impl}
\begin{tabular}{@{}llr@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Subsystem} & \textbf{Language} & \textbf{LoC} \\
\midrule
Grammar Compiler & Rust & 18,000 \\
Transformation Algebra + MR Checker & Rust + Python & 12,000 \\
Input Generator & Rust & 8,000 \\
Pipeline Instrumentor & Python + Rust bridge & 15,000 \\
Fault Localizer & Rust + Python & 12,000 \\
Grammar-Aware Shrinker & Rust & 12,000 \\
Coverage Analyzer & Rust & 6,000 \\
Counterexample DB + Reports & Rust + Python & 8,000 \\
Spec Language & Rust & 4,000 \\
Test Scheduler & Rust & 4,000 \\
Evaluation Harness & Python & 8,000 \\
\midrule
\textbf{Total} & & \textbf{$\sim$107,000} \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

The Rust/Python split reflects profiling reality: grammar compilation, transformation composition, and shrinking are CPU-bound combinatorial operations where Rust's performance is essential (millions of derivations per second during shrinking). NLP pipeline execution is Python-native (spaCy and HuggingFace are Python libraries), so instrumentation must be Python. The PyO3 bridge ($\sim$3K LoC within the instrumentor) connects the two.

The grammar contains 847 production rules, 12,400 lexical entries with frequency weights, and 23 feature types for unification. The morphological transducer covers 98.7\% of English inflectional forms (validated against CELEX).


% ============================================================================
\section{Evaluation}
\label{sec:eval}
% ============================================================================

We evaluate \textsc{MetamorFault} on seven experiments across two pipeline frameworks (spaCy 3.7, HuggingFace Transformers 4.38) and three NLP tasks (NER, sentiment analysis, dependency parsing).

\subsection{Experiment 1: Fault Localization Accuracy}

We inject synthetic faults into individual pipeline stages and measure whether \textsc{MetamorFault} correctly identifies the faulty stage. Faults include: (a) randomly perturbing POS tags with 5\% probability, (b) deleting random dependency arcs with 3\% probability, (c) corrupting NER spans by shifting boundaries by 1 token.

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{Fault localization accuracy on fault-injected pipelines (100 faults per stage).}
\label{tab:exp1}
\begin{tabular}{@{}lrrrr@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Tool} & \textbf{Top-1 Acc.} & \textbf{Top-2 Acc.} & \textbf{Intro vs. Amp.} & \textbf{Time (s)} \\
\midrule
\textsc{MetamorFault} & 89.2\% & 96.7\% & 84.1\% & 127 \\
CheckList & 0\% & 0\% & N/A & 43 \\
TextFlint & 0\% & 0\% & N/A & 51 \\
Robustness Gym & 0\% & 0\% & N/A & 38 \\
Manual (per-stage prints) & 71.4\% & 85.2\% & 52.3\% & 1,847 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

CheckList, TextFlint, and Robustness Gym score 0\% because they perform no per-stage localization---they report only end-to-end pass/fail. Manual debugging (inserting print statements between stages) achieves 71.4\% top-1 accuracy but takes 14.5$\times$ longer and cannot distinguish introduction from amplification reliably.

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\begin{tikzpicture}
\begin{axis}[
    ybar,
    bar width=15pt,
    ylabel={Top-1 Accuracy (\%)},
    symbolic x coords={MetamorFault,CheckList,TextFlint,Rob.Gym,Manual},
    xtick=data,
    ymin=0, ymax=100,
    width=0.75\textwidth,
    height=5.5cm,
    nodes near coords,
    nodes near coords style={font=\small},
]
\addplot[fill=blue!60] coordinates {(MetamorFault,89.2) (CheckList,0) (TextFlint,0) (Rob.Gym,0) (Manual,71.4)};
\end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}
\caption{Fault localization accuracy comparison.}
\label{fig:exp1}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Experiment 2: Counterexample Minimality}

We compare grammar-aware shrinking (GCHDD) against string-level delta debugging and no shrinking on 200 metamorphic violations.

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{Counterexample size comparison (median tokens).}
\label{tab:exp2}
\begin{tabular}{@{}lrrr@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Method} & \textbf{Median Tokens} & \textbf{Grammatical?} & \textbf{Transform OK?} \\
\midrule
No shrinking & 23.4 & Yes & Yes \\
String-level DD & 8.7 & 12\% & 4\% \\
GCHDD (ours) & 6.3 & 100\% & 100\% \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

GCHDD produces counterexamples 73\% smaller than the original input (23.4 $\to$ 6.3 tokens). String-level DD achieves slightly smaller size (8.7 tokens) but produces ungrammatical fragments 88\% of the time, rendering them useless for debugging. GCHDD maintains 100\% grammaticality and 100\% transformation applicability by construction.

\subsection{Experiment 3: Coverage Efficiency}

We compare algebraic coverage optimization (using the MR composition theorem to plan test generation) against random testing on achieving pairwise transformation $\times$ pipeline stage coverage.

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
