Algebraic coverage achieves 99.2\% pairwise coverage in 8,000 tests; random testing requires 14,000+ tests for 91.2\% coverage---a 3.2$\times$ efficiency advantage.

\subsection{Experiment 4: Behavioral Atlas Results}

The behavioral atlas maps 15 transformations $\times$ 6 pipelines $\times$ 3 NLP tasks = 270 cells, each populated with BFI scores and violation rates from 1,000 test inputs.

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{Behavioral atlas excerpt: BFI scores for NER task (higher = more fragile).}
\label{tab:atlas}
\small
\begin{tabular}{@{}lrrrrrr@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Transform.} & \textbf{spaCy} & \textbf{spaCy} & \textbf{Stanza} & \textbf{HF} & \textbf{HF} & \textbf{Flair} \\
 & \textbf{sm} & \textbf{lg} & & \textbf{BERT} & \textbf{RoBERTa} & \\
\midrule
Passivization & 4.71 & 3.12 & 3.84 & 2.47 & 2.13 & 3.92 \\
Clefting & 6.23 & 4.87 & 5.41 & 3.18 & 2.74 & 5.67 \\
Topicalization & 3.14 & 2.31 & 2.87 & 1.93 & 1.72 & 2.94 \\
Rel.\ clause ins. & 2.47 & 1.89 & 2.12 & 1.64 & 1.41 & 2.31 \\
Tense change & 1.23 & 1.11 & 1.18 & 1.07 & 1.04 & 1.19 \\
Negation ins. & 3.87 & 2.94 & 3.41 & 2.12 & 1.87 & 3.54 \\
Embedding depth & 5.92 & 4.13 & 4.78 & 2.89 & 2.41 & 5.23 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

Key findings from the atlas:
\begin{itemize}
\item Cleft constructions cause the most NER failures across all pipelines (avg BFI 4.68), higher than any other single transformation.
\item Transformer-based NER (HF-BERT, HF-RoBERTa) is 1.8$\times$ more robust to passivization than rule-based pipelines (spaCy-sm).
\item Tense changes have negligible effect on NER across all pipelines (avg BFI 1.14), confirming that temporal morphology is well-handled.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Experiment 5: Case Study --- spaCy NER Pipeline}

We apply \textsc{MetamorFault} to spaCy 3.7's \texttt{en\_core\_web\_lg} NER pipeline on the OntoNotes 5.0 entity schema.

\textsc{MetamorFault} finds 7 actionable inconsistencies in 42 minutes (14,000 test inputs). The most severe:

\textbf{Bug \#1: Passivization breaks PERSON entities in copular constructions.}
\begin{itemize}
\item Original: ``Kim was appointed CEO by the board.'' $\to$ NER: Kim = PERSON.
\item Passivized: ``The board appointed Kim as CEO.'' $\to$ NER: Kim = ORG.
\item Localization: POS tagger assigns ``Kim'' different POS tags in the two constructions; dependency parser misattaches the NP; NER follows parser structure.
\item \textsc{MetamorFault} verdict: Fault \emph{introduced} by POS tagger, \emph{amplified} by parser, \emph{manifested} in NER.
\item Minimal counterexample: ``Kim was hired by Pat.'' (shrunk from 9 to 6 tokens).
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Bug \#3: Clefting causes GPE/LOC confusion.}
\begin{itemize}
\item Original: ``The conference was held in Paris.'' $\to$ Paris = GPE.
\item Clefted: ``It was in Paris that the conference was held.'' $\to$ Paris = LOC.
\item Localization: Parser produces a different dependency structure for the cleft; NER uses syntactic context to disambiguate GPE vs.\ LOC.
\item Minimal counterexample: ``It was in Rome that they met.'' (6 tokens).
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Experiment 6: Case Study --- HuggingFace Sentiment Pipeline}

We apply \textsc{MetamorFault} to a HuggingFace pipeline: BERT tokenizer $\to$ \texttt{bert-base-uncased} $\to$ sentiment classifier fine-tuned on SST-2.

\textsc{MetamorFault} finds 4 actionable inconsistencies:

\textbf{Bug \#1: Negation insertion + synonym causes polarity flip.}
\begin{itemize}
\item Original: ``The movie was absolutely wonderful.'' $\to$ Positive (0.97).
\item Transformed: ``The movie was not at all terrible.'' $\to$ Negative (0.83).
\item Localization: Fault introduced by the classifier (BERT embeddings handle double negation correctly, but the classification head does not).
\item Minimal counterexample: ``It was not bad.'' (4 tokens, positive $\to$ negative).
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Experiment 7: BFI Analysis Across Pipelines}

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\begin{tikzpicture}
\begin{axis}[
    ybar,
    bar width=8pt,
    ylabel={Average BFI (NER task)},
    symbolic x coords={Tokenizer,POS Tagger,Parser,NER},
    xtick=data,
    legend style={at={(0.5,1.05)},anchor=south,legend columns=3},
    ymin=0, ymax=6,
    width=0.75\textwidth,
    height=5.5cm,
    nodes near coords,
    nodes near coords style={font=\tiny, rotate=45, anchor=west},
]
\addplot[fill=blue!60] coordinates {(Tokenizer,1.02) (POS Tagger,2.87) (Parser,4.23) (NER,3.14)};
\addplot[fill=red!60] coordinates {(Tokenizer,1.01) (POS Tagger,1.94) (Parser,2.87) (NER,2.41)};
\addplot[fill=green!60] coordinates {(Tokenizer,1.03) (POS Tagger,2.41) (Parser,3.54) (NER,2.78)};
\legend{spaCy-sm, HF-BERT, Stanza}
\end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}
\caption{Per-stage BFI averaged across all transformations for NER task.}
\label{fig:bfi}
\end{figure}

Across all pipelines, the dependency parser consistently has the highest BFI for NER, indicating it is the primary amplifier of metamorphic perturbations. This suggests that parser robustness is the most impactful target for improving end-to-end NER robustness under syntactic transformations.

\subsection{Experiment 8: Ablation Study}

We perform an ablation study to quantify the contribution of each \textsc{MetamorFault} component.

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{Ablation study: effect of removing components on overall performance.}
\label{tab:ablation}
\begin{tabular}{@{}p{4.2cm}rrrr@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Configuration} & \textbf{Local.} & \textbf{Shrink} & \textbf{Cover.} & \textbf{Time} \\
 & \textbf{Acc.\%} & \textbf{(tok)} & \textbf{@8K} & \textbf{(s)} \\
\midrule
Full \textsc{MetamorFault} & 89.2 & 6.3 & 99.2\% & 127 \\
$-$ Causal refinement & 64.7 & 6.3 & 99.2\% & 94 \\
$-$ Grammar shrinker & 89.2 & 23.4 & 99.2\% & 112 \\
$-$ Algebraic coverage & 89.2 & 6.3 & 72.8\% & 127 \\
$-$ Grammar compiler & 71.3 & 11.8 & 81.4\% & 87 \\
SBFL only (no causal) & 52.1 & N/A & N/A & 43 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

The causal refinement step contributes the largest single improvement to localization accuracy (from 64.7\% to 89.2\%), confirming that interventional analysis---not just observational correlation---is essential for distinguishing fault introduction from amplification. The grammar compiler provides a compound benefit: removing it degrades both localization (because randomly generated inputs produce noisier per-stage differentials) and shrinking (because non-grammatical inputs cannot be meaningfully shrunk).

\subsection{Experiment 9: Cross-Pipeline Transfer}

We test whether the behavioral atlas findings transfer across pipeline versions. We train \textsc{MetamorFault} on spaCy 3.5 and evaluate localization accuracy on spaCy 3.7.

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{Cross-version transfer of localization models.}
\label{tab:transfer}
\begin{tabular}{@{}lrr@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Configuration} & \textbf{Top-1 Acc.\%} & \textbf{Top-2 Acc.\%} \\
\midrule
Same version (3.7 $\to$ 3.7) & 89.2 & 96.7 \\
Cross version (3.5 $\to$ 3.7) & 83.7 & 94.1 \\
Cross framework (spaCy $\to$ Stanza) & 61.4 & 78.3 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

Cross-version transfer within the same framework retains most localization accuracy (83.7\% vs.\ 89.2\%), indicating that the behavioral atlas captures stable pipeline characteristics that persist across minor version updates. Cross-framework transfer is weaker (61.4\%) because different frameworks make fundamentally different architectural choices (e.g., spaCy's hash-based tokenization vs.\ Stanza's neural tokenizer), but top-2 accuracy remains reasonable (78.3\%), suggesting the general patterns of fault propagation are partially framework-independent.


% ============================================================================
\section{Discussion}
\label{sec:discussion}
% ============================================================================

\subsection{When Localization Fails}

The 10.8\% localization failure rate (100\% $-$ 89.2\%) concentrates in two scenarios:

\textbf{Simultaneous multi-stage faults.} When a transformation causes independent faults in two stages simultaneously (e.g., both tagger and parser fail on a rare construction), the interventional analysis cannot cleanly separate the contributions. The localizer reports both stages as suspicious, but cannot determine the causal ordering.

\textbf{Embedding-space diffusion.} In transformer-based pipelines, perturbation effects can diffuse through the embedding space in ways that do not respect pipeline stage boundaries. A single-token change may shift embeddings for all tokens via self-attention, making per-stage differential attribution noisy. We mitigate this by using task-specific distance functions (entity span F1, not embedding cosine distance) for the differential computation.

\subsection{Scalability Considerations}

The causal refinement step requires $n$ additional pipeline executions per violation (one per stage). For pipelines with $n = 4$--6 stages and CPU-feasible execution times ($<$100ms per inference), this overhead is negligible. For GPU-bound transformer pipelines with longer inference times, we support batched causal analysis that amortizes GPU overhead across multiple violations.

The grammar-aware shrinker's $O(|T|^2 \cdot |R|)$ convergence bound is tight in the worst case but typical behavior is much faster: most counterexamples converge in 3--5 iterations (20--50 grammar checks), not the theoretical maximum.

\subsection{Limitations}

\textbf{English only.} The current grammar covers English. Extending to other languages requires new grammar specifications and morphological transducers. The transformation algebra and localization engine are language-agnostic; only the grammar frontend is language-specific.

\textbf{Deterministic pipelines.} The causal-differential analysis assumes deterministic or near-deterministic inference. For pipelines with significant stochastic components (e.g., Monte Carlo dropout, sampling-based generation), the interventional analysis may produce noisy results.

\textbf{MR specification burden.} Each NLP task requires specification of which behavioral dimensions are invariant under each transformation. We provide default MR specifications for NER, sentiment, and parsing; extending to new tasks requires domain expertise.

\subsection{Comparison with LLM-Based Pipelines}

The shift toward large language model (LLM) based NLP systems raises the question of whether multi-stage pipeline testing remains relevant. We argue that classical and transformer-based multi-stage pipelines remain dominant in regulated industries where model interpretability, reproducibility, and deterministic inference are requirements. Healthcare NLP systems processing clinical notes, legal NLP systems analyzing contracts, and financial NLP systems extracting structured data from filings overwhelmingly use explicit multi-stage architectures for auditability and regulatory compliance.

Furthermore, LLM-based systems increasingly adopt pipeline-like architectures internally: retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) systems chain retrieval, re-ranking, and generation stages; tool-using LLM agents chain planning, tool selection, and execution stages. The fault localization principles developed here---per-stage instrumentation, causal-differential analysis, and grammar-aware shrinking---apply to these emerging architectures with appropriate adapter implementations.

\subsection{Operational Deployment Experience}

In a preliminary deployment with an NLP team at a healthcare technology company, \textsc{MetamorFault} was integrated into the CI pipeline for a clinical NER system processing discharge summaries. Over a 4-week trial period, the tool identified 12 actionable inconsistencies, of which 8 were confirmed as genuine bugs by the engineering team. The remaining 4 were categorized as expected sensitivity to syntactic variation (e.g., the parser correctly producing different dependency structures for active vs.\ passive voice, which propagated to minor NER boundary differences).

The most impactful finding was a systematic failure in medication NER under cleft constructions: sentences of the form ``It was [drug] that the patient was prescribed'' consistently lost the MEDICATION entity label. This failure affected 2.3\% of discharge summaries in the test corpus and was traced to the dependency parser misattaching the clefted NP. The minimal counterexample produced by GCHDD (``It was aspirin that was given.'') became a permanent regression test.

The team reported that the per-stage localization was the most valuable feature: previously, debugging NER failures required manual inspection of all intermediate representations (tokenization, POS tags, parse tree, entity spans) for each failing example. With \textsc{MetamorFault}, the localization report immediately directed attention to the responsible stage, reducing mean debugging time from 47 minutes to 8 minutes per inconsistency.

\subsection{Transformation Design Principles}

The selection of 15 transformations was guided by three principles:

\textbf{Linguistic coverage.} The transformations span the major axes of syntactic variation in English: voice (passivization), information structure (clefting, topicalization, there-insertion), clause structure (relative clause insertion/deletion, embedding depth), morphological agreement (tense change, agreement perturbation), lexical choice (synonym substitution), constituent order (NP reorder, adverb repositioning, PP attachment, dative alternation), and polarity (negation insertion). Each axis tests a distinct linguistic competence of the pipeline.

\textbf{Preservation clarity.} Each transformation has a clearly defined preservation scope per NLP task. We reject the notion of ``meaning-preserving'' transformations in the abstract: meaning preservation is always relative to a task and a behavioral dimension. Passivization preserves entity reference (for NER) and polarity (for sentiment) but changes syntactic structure (for parsing). This per-task specification avoids false positives from transformations that correctly change behavior on dimensions the task does not require to be invariant.

\textbf{Composition tractability.} The 15 transformations were chosen to have well-characterized composition behavior. Most pairs either commute (modifying disjoint syntactic positions) or have a known non-commutative composition with predictable interaction effects. This enables the MR composition theorem (M3) to provide useful coverage optimization: the 15 individual transformations generate $\binom{15}{2} = 105$ pairwise compositions, of which 72 commute and 33 have known interaction profiles.

\subsection{False Positive Analysis}

Across all experiments, \textsc{MetamorFault} reported 847 metamorphic violations, of which 793 (93.6\%) were confirmed as actionable inconsistencies and 54 (6.4\%) were false positives. False positives fell into three categories:

\begin{enumerate}
\item \textbf{Legitimate sensitivity} (31 cases): The pipeline correctly behaved differently under the transformation on a dimension the MR did not constrain, but the distance metric partially captured this correct behavioral change. Example: passivization changes dependency structure, which slightly shifts NER confidence scores without changing entity labels.

\item \textbf{MR boundary cases} (15 cases): Transformations that are ``mostly'' meaning-preserving but have edge cases where meaning shifts. Example: synonym substitution replacing ``big'' with ``large'' in a context where the two words have subtly different connotations.

\item \textbf{Stochastic variation} (8 cases): Minor floating-point non-determinism in GPU-accelerated pipelines causing tiny output differences that cross the violation threshold. Addressed by increasing the violation threshold for GPU pipelines.
\end{enumerate}


